1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:13,840
 The Shroud of Turin is about to be examined in a way it has never been before.

2
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:21,460
 The most famous thing about the Shroud now is that it is a medieval fake and not the burial

3
00:00:21,460 --> 00:00:25,280
 cloth of Christ as millions of people have believed.

4
00:00:25,280 --> 00:00:30,520
 That was the verdict of a carbon-14 test done exactly twenty years ago.

5
00:00:30,520 --> 00:00:36,520
 But the irresistible force of science seems to have hit an immovable object.

6
00:00:36,520 --> 00:00:41,900
 New evidence has appeared which contradicts the results of the carbon-14 test.

7
00:00:41,900 --> 00:00:51,920
 So why won't this image of a naked and battered man just lie down and die?

8
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:57,980
 There is one very good reason: no one has been able to work out how the forger did it.

9
00:00:57,980 --> 00:01:04,160
 No one, despite many attempts, has been able to produce an image with the same physical characteristics.

10
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:06,160
 It's a mystery.

11
00:01:06,160 --> 00:01:11,160
 And into this vacuum has rushed a new and for many unthinkable question.

12
00:01:11,160 --> 00:01:18,220
 Is it after all not the Shroud that may be found wanting but the carbon-14 test applied to it?

13
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:25,220
 On the 20th anniversary of that test, physicists are preparing a new carbon-14 test.

14
00:01:25,220 --> 00:01:30,400
 It will show if the original carbon-14 test could have lied.

15
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:34,840
 So just what is the new evidence relating to the Shroud of Turin?

16
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:40,300
 And could it resurrect the Shroud as the most potent relic of Christianity?

17
00:01:40,300 --> 00:02:06,300
 I am embarking on a journey that will span three continents and take me to the very heart of Christian history and to the people that have closely examined the Shroud.

18
00:02:06,300 --> 00:02:22,300
 Turin sits in the plain at the foot of the Alps in Northern Italy.

19
00:02:22,300 --> 00:02:28,300
 This is the home of the Shroud, the Cathedral of John the Baptist.

20
00:02:28,300 --> 00:02:31,300
 Well, this is quite a moment for me.

21
00:02:31,300 --> 00:02:35,700
 My first awareness of the Shroud came when I was at school in the 80s.

22
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:42,600
 A lot of new research appeared to hold out the prospect that it was, indeed, the most important relic in Christendom.

23
00:02:50,860 --> 00:02:58,260
 The last time the Shroud was shown was in 2000, and it's not due to be seen again until 2010 at the earliest.

24
00:02:58,260 --> 00:03:02,260
 Visitors have to make do with the site of its fireproof case.

25
00:03:02,260 --> 00:03:07,860
 But already there's a surprise in store.

26
00:03:07,860 --> 00:03:10,260
 Something remarkable has just happened.

27
00:03:10,260 --> 00:03:13,260
 News has come to me from the Cardinal's secretary.

28
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:23,660
 The Cardinal has agreed for its veil to be lifted for us.

29
00:03:23,660 --> 00:03:29,260
 In this side chapel, the windows are being blacked out and the humidity and temperature carefully measured.

30
00:03:29,260 --> 00:03:39,260
 Under considerable secrecy, this room is being prepared so that our camera teams can film the Shroud for the first time in high definition.

31
00:03:39,260 --> 00:03:46,260
 While the preparations take place, I want to understand the key features of the Shroud.

32
00:03:46,260 --> 00:03:56,260
 The first thing that strikes you is that since the carbon-14 test, the Church makes no claims for its authenticity.

33
00:03:56,260 --> 00:04:00,260
 But it does maintain its importance as an object of devotion.

34
00:04:00,260 --> 00:04:07,260
 Behind that glass and beneath that cover lies the finest Italian engineering.

35
00:04:07,260 --> 00:04:14,260
 Designed to keep it safe and in an atmosphere of inert gas, monitored minute by minute.

36
00:04:14,260 --> 00:04:23,260
 Professor Bruno Barberis is the curator of the museum dedicated to the Shroud.

37
00:04:23,260 --> 00:04:27,260
 And a visit to the museum begins with a film.

38
00:04:32,260 --> 00:04:37,260
 One intriguing revelation is that throughout its history, the Shroud has often been displayed in public.

39
00:04:37,260 --> 00:04:42,260
 It may seem like a trivial detail, but it could be important to the investigation.

40
00:04:42,260 --> 00:04:49,260
 Could the Shroud have been contaminated in any way and so distort its true age?

41
00:04:49,260 --> 00:05:00,260
 Another relevant detail is that artists have tried to imagine how the cloth must have been wrapped around the body to create the image of the front and back.

42
00:05:00,260 --> 00:05:05,260
 The answer could shed light on the age of the cloth.

43
00:05:05,260 --> 00:05:17,260
 In 1532, a fire melted the metal box in which the Shroud was kept and it left behind a geometrical pattern of burns.

44
00:05:17,260 --> 00:05:21,260
 Miraculously, the image was preserved intact.

45
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:31,260
 And finally, a piece of information that goes to the heart of the debate over the age of the Shroud.

46
00:05:31,260 --> 00:05:43,260
 All we can know for certain is that before Turin, the Shroud can only be reliably traced back to the village of Lire in France, where it was in the possession of this man.

47
00:05:44,260 --> 00:05:51,260
 The Shroud is the Shroud, who first exhibited it in 1360.

48
00:05:51,260 --> 00:05:58,260
 That date is very significant because Carbon-14 dates the Shroud at 1325, plus or minus 65 years.

49
00:05:58,260 --> 00:06:00,260
 It all seems to check out.

50
00:06:01,260 --> 00:06:11,260
 My first impression of the Shroud then is that, on the face of it, it would make sense to dismiss it as medieval forgery.

51
00:06:11,260 --> 00:06:17,260
 But as I am about to discover, there is more, a great deal more to this cloth than meets the eye.

52
00:06:18,260 --> 00:06:25,260
 The day for the filming has arrived.

53
00:06:25,260 --> 00:06:33,260
 These will be the first high-definition moving images ever taken.

54
00:06:33,260 --> 00:06:36,260
 We are turning over.

55
00:06:36,260 --> 00:06:38,260
 We are running up.

56
00:06:38,260 --> 00:06:41,260
 To protect it, only the minimum amount of light is used.

57
00:06:42,260 --> 00:06:54,260
 It took me a while to pick everything out, but then it became quite clear.

58
00:06:54,260 --> 00:07:01,260
 Lying between the geometric patches from the fire, the image of the front and back of a man's body,

59
00:07:01,260 --> 00:07:07,260
 with what seem like scourge marks, and the very specific wounds of a crucifixion.

60
00:07:11,260 --> 00:07:16,260
 The cloth itself is about four meters of linen, with traces of cotton.

61
00:07:16,260 --> 00:07:20,260
 It has a distinctive herringbone weave,

62
00:07:20,260 --> 00:07:24,260
 and the scorches from the 1532 fire.

63
00:07:24,260 --> 00:07:28,260
 These show it was once folded in '48.

64
00:07:28,260 --> 00:07:36,260
 And another curious set of L-shaped scars show that at one time, it must also have been folded in four.

65
00:07:36,260 --> 00:07:39,260
 These observations could be important.

66
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:44,260
 This is the image the shroud reveals to the naked eye.

67
00:07:44,260 --> 00:07:49,260
 But with the help of some technology, the eye can see more.

68
00:07:49,260 --> 00:08:00,260
 By first removing the colour and then reversing light and shade, we create a negative of the image.

69
00:08:01,260 --> 00:08:10,260
 Photography first captured this a century ago, but today it can be done at the press of a button.

70
00:08:10,260 --> 00:08:16,260
 This is a clearer image of the figure on the cloth.

71
00:08:17,260 --> 00:08:18,260
 This is the true positive.

72
00:08:18,260 --> 00:08:29,260
 It's the image on the cloth that is in fact a negative.

73
00:08:29,260 --> 00:08:30,260
 This is the camera which revealed to the world a much clearer image of the shroud.

74
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:42,260
 This is the camera which revealed to the world a much clearer image of the shroud.

75
00:08:42,260 --> 00:08:48,260
 In its negative form, the shroud was somehow more recognisable and easily discernible.

76
00:08:49,260 --> 00:09:01,260
 And what's more, photography meant that the image of the shroud could travel far and wide and interest in it began to grow around the world.

77
00:09:02,260 --> 00:09:05,260
 For believers, the appeal was irresistible.

78
00:09:05,260 --> 00:09:13,260
 The shroud seemed to hold out the promise of a tangible contact with Christ himself at the crisis of his suffering on the cross.

79
00:09:14,260 --> 00:09:16,260
 And here were the key identifiers.

80
00:09:16,260 --> 00:09:19,260
 The wounds from the lance in the side.

81
00:09:19,260 --> 00:09:23,260
 And the crown of thorns.

82
00:09:23,260 --> 00:09:27,260
 But carbon-14 ended that hope.

83
00:09:27,260 --> 00:09:30,260
 And many religious hearts were broken.

84
00:09:30,260 --> 00:09:36,260
 A couple of generations have since grown up knowing almost nothing about the shroud.

85
00:09:36,260 --> 00:09:42,260
 But whatever the result of the carbon-14 test, the shroud has remained an enigma.

86
00:09:44,260 --> 00:09:47,260
 And the enigma is this.

87
00:09:47,260 --> 00:09:53,260
 If the shroud of Turin is a medieval fake, then how exactly was the image forged?

88
00:09:53,260 --> 00:10:03,260
 Lying in the shadow of the Rocky Mountains in the United States is Colorado Springs.

89
00:10:10,260 --> 00:10:15,260
 It's the home of the man who has studied the shroud closer and longer than anyone else.

90
00:10:15,260 --> 00:10:22,260
 John Jackson is a doctor in cosmology and lecturer in physics.

91
00:10:22,260 --> 00:10:27,260
 Together with his wife Rebecca, he runs the Turin Shroud Center of Colorado.

92
00:10:28,260 --> 00:10:38,260
 Through his research, he has had one of the few full-size high-definition still images of the shroud for some time.

93
00:10:38,260 --> 00:10:52,260
 In 1978, when interest in the shroud was at its height, he led a large team of scientists to Turin, where they examined the shroud for a week.

94
00:10:53,260 --> 00:10:57,260
 No one since has secured such full access to the cloth.

95
00:10:57,260 --> 00:11:06,260
 Significant amounts of different types of data were extracted.

96
00:11:06,260 --> 00:11:12,260
 Jackson became the primary custodian of this data, and he has continued the work.

97
00:11:13,260 --> 00:11:18,260
 Only now does he feel ready to share his findings exclusively with us.

98
00:11:18,260 --> 00:11:25,260
 And like everyone else, Jackson wants to solve the riddle of the shroud.

99
00:11:25,260 --> 00:11:30,260
 If it's a 14th-century forgery, then how was it done?

100
00:11:30,260 --> 00:11:36,260
 Could a medieval artist have created the distinctive properties of this image?

101
00:11:37,260 --> 00:11:41,260
 The first thing Jackson established is that the cloth can be wrapped around a body.

102
00:11:41,260 --> 00:11:47,260
 The blood stains on the back and front of the cloth match exactly where they should.

103
00:11:47,260 --> 00:11:53,260
 Place it over the three-dimensional man that we have here.

104
00:11:54,260 --> 00:12:00,260
 Now, I'm going to pull this intentionally straight.

105
00:12:00,260 --> 00:12:06,260
 And I would like you to notice, first of all, that this blood stain right here,

106
00:12:06,260 --> 00:12:11,260
 which is this at the bottom of the feet, is totally...

107
00:12:11,260 --> 00:12:13,260
 Hanging off the end.

108
00:12:14,260 --> 00:12:15,260
 Totally off image.

109
00:12:15,260 --> 00:12:19,260
 Look what happens when we make the hands aligned properly.

110
00:12:19,260 --> 00:12:24,260
 Look now what happens to the blood stain at the bottom of the cloth.

111
00:12:24,260 --> 00:12:26,260
 That matches.

112
00:12:26,260 --> 00:12:29,260
 It's exactly where a nail would have been.

113
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:34,260
 Once key features were aligned, everything else fell into place.

114
00:12:34,260 --> 00:12:37,260
 Even the stains from one end of the cloth to the other.

115
00:12:37,260 --> 00:12:43,260
 If we're dealing with a medieval relic, then it's one that's been meticulously created.

116
00:12:44,260 --> 00:12:47,260
 And we know that the blood stains are not paint.

117
00:12:47,260 --> 00:12:52,260
 Jackson's team identified it as blood in 1978.

118
00:12:52,260 --> 00:12:59,260
 But what of the image itself?

119
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:05,260
 The image on the shroud has some very interesting characteristics to it.

120
00:13:05,260 --> 00:13:10,260
 And these are not only interesting, but they're scientific characteristics.

121
00:13:11,260 --> 00:13:14,260
 The simplest hypothesis is that the forger painted the image.

122
00:13:14,260 --> 00:13:18,260
 The proof would be the presence of a medium to bind the pigment.

123
00:13:18,260 --> 00:13:25,260
 We are going in now to a close-up of the darkest part of the image, the nose.

124
00:13:25,260 --> 00:13:29,260
 And further, to a microscopic picture of the same area.

125
00:13:32,260 --> 00:13:34,260
 The image is only on the surface fibrils of the cloth.

126
00:13:34,260 --> 00:13:40,260
 These fibrils, which are on the order of the size or the diameter of a human hair.

127
00:13:40,260 --> 00:13:43,260
 These are the fibrils that are twisted together to make threads.

128
00:13:43,260 --> 00:13:48,260
 If you look, these fibrils are individually colored.

129
00:13:48,260 --> 00:13:52,260
 They bear that color that is the body image at the microscopic level.

130
00:13:53,260 --> 00:13:57,260
 Notice that those fibrils are not cemented together by any kind of paint.

131
00:13:57,260 --> 00:14:04,260
 What we see, and this is the observation, microscopically, is that the individual fibrils of the shroud are colored.

132
00:14:04,260 --> 00:14:09,260
 To get a better understanding, we need to look at the cloth sideways on.

133
00:14:09,260 --> 00:14:17,260
 If we magnify its thickness, we find that the fibrils that bear the image are literally just on the surface.

134
00:14:18,260 --> 00:14:21,260
 Nothing has seen into the cloth below.

135
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:25,260
 What this observation does, and this illustrates the scientific method,

136
00:14:25,260 --> 00:14:33,260
 is the hypothesis of an artist using a pigment that has some viscosity to it,

137
00:14:33,260 --> 00:14:37,260
 is excluded, I believe, by this singular observation on the shroud.

138
00:14:37,260 --> 00:14:44,260
 If the image is not a painting,

139
00:14:45,260 --> 00:14:51,260
 Jackson considered the idea that an embalmer subjected a real body to the horrors of crucifixion,

140
00:14:51,260 --> 00:14:53,260
 and then wrapped a cloth around it.

141
00:14:53,260 --> 00:15:03,260
 But a simple look at the image of the face shows that contact between the body and the cloth alone

142
00:15:03,260 --> 00:15:05,260
 could not have formed the image.

143
00:15:05,260 --> 00:15:10,260
 The eye sockets and the other recesses of the body, as well as the hair at the side,

144
00:15:10,260 --> 00:15:13,260
 would never have been in direct contact with the body.

145
00:15:14,260 --> 00:15:17,260
 And if they were, the resulting image would look like this.

146
00:15:17,260 --> 00:15:26,260
 If the image is a fake, it can't be the work of either a painter or an embalmer.

147
00:15:26,260 --> 00:15:32,260
 Of course, the carbon-14 test still points to the shroud being a medieval relic.

148
00:15:32,260 --> 00:15:38,260
 But Jackson has identified two properties of the image that a forger would have had to reproduce,

149
00:15:39,260 --> 00:15:42,260
 that only modern technology can detect.

150
00:15:42,260 --> 00:15:48,260
 The first is the fact that the naked eye only sees a negative image of the body.

151
00:15:49,260 --> 00:15:57,260
 This is important because if we're going to think of the image as being the work of an artist,

152
00:15:57,260 --> 00:16:07,260
 then it would seem that what you have to deal with is the idea of somebody composing the image in a negative reverse

153
00:16:08,260 --> 00:16:15,260
 to the way we normally see a human being and put this onto a piece of cloth, a long piece of cloth,

154
00:16:15,260 --> 00:16:20,260
 with a technique which also has definable characteristics.

155
00:16:21,260 --> 00:16:22,260
 This is a very difficult thing to imagine.

156
00:16:22,260 --> 00:16:31,260
 You have to remember that whoever would have, or a hypothetical artist, would have not had the luxury of being able to check his work.

157
00:16:32,260 --> 00:16:40,260
 The second unique property of the image is one discovered by Jackson himself, its three-dimensional quality.

158
00:16:40,260 --> 00:16:49,260
 He discovered from his experimental wrappings that the intensity of the image varies with the distance the body is from the cloth.

159
00:16:49,260 --> 00:16:54,260
 The tip of the nose, for example, is darker than the hollow of the eye.

160
00:16:55,260 --> 00:17:01,260
 I wanted to know if we could see this with our new high-definition images.

161
00:17:01,260 --> 00:17:09,260
 And sure enough, with the simplest press of a button in our editing suite, this 3D quality is revealed.

162
00:17:09,260 --> 00:17:21,260
 I was astounded when we were able to do this that the brightness surface that you create by the computer

163
00:17:22,260 --> 00:17:26,260
 as you can see here, very much like a three-dimensional person, particularly the face.

164
00:17:26,260 --> 00:17:32,260
 If you look at the facial structure, you've got the nose in proper relationship to the cheeks,

165
00:17:32,260 --> 00:17:36,260
 which are in proper relationship to the eye sockets and so forth.

166
00:17:36,260 --> 00:17:40,260
 These special properties of the cloth narrow the options.

167
00:17:40,260 --> 00:17:43,260
 Maybe the forger was a sculptor.

168
00:17:43,260 --> 00:17:48,260
 A medieval technique for creating both properties is bar relief.

169
00:17:49,260 --> 00:17:52,260
 A sculptor creates a 3D model in stone or metal.

170
00:17:52,260 --> 00:18:03,260
 To transfer the image onto the cloth, the bar relief is heated and the cloth placed over it long enough to be scorched.

171
00:18:03,260 --> 00:18:07,260
 It's an option that Jackson has experimented with.

172
00:18:08,260 --> 00:18:23,260
 The real test of this method is whether the heated sculpture can scorch an image on the surface and only on the surface of the cloth.

173
00:18:24,260 --> 00:18:29,260
 So I used that, making a hot bar relief, trying to impress that on the cloth.

174
00:18:29,260 --> 00:18:36,260
 And yes, you can get some images that could have some pseudo three-dimensional quality and also a high resolution.

175
00:18:36,260 --> 00:18:48,260
 But the problem there is that to put a surface discoloration on the cloth, on the fibrils, heat will discolor through the thickness of the shroud in about,

176
00:18:49,260 --> 00:18:52,260
 It's about one one-hundredth to one-tenth of a second.

177
00:18:52,260 --> 00:19:02,260
 So you would have to have the bar relief on the cloth and take it away on a timescale like that in order to be consistent with what we observe.

178
00:19:02,260 --> 00:19:04,260
 So it just goes on and on.

179
00:19:04,260 --> 00:19:07,260
 Problems that just don't seem to work.

180
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:13,260
 To avoid this problem, some tests have daubed paint to transfer the bar relief onto the cloth.

181
00:19:13,260 --> 00:19:17,260
 The result does show some negative and 3D qualities.

182
00:19:17,260 --> 00:19:20,260
 The trouble is that they are distorted and crude.

183
00:19:20,260 --> 00:19:28,260
 Also, this method uses paint and the absence of any evidence of a binding medium on the cloth does rule that out.

184
00:19:29,260 --> 00:19:41,260
 I must say that anyone who wants to try to explain the shroud image, and this work needs to continue most definitely.

185
00:19:41,260 --> 00:19:51,260
 But one has to make sure that you're working on a hypothesis that can explain the totality of all image characteristics.

186
00:19:52,260 --> 00:19:53,260
 You can't just go and pick and choose.

187
00:19:53,260 --> 00:19:54,260
 Not just the bits, yeah.

188
00:19:54,260 --> 00:19:57,260
 You can't pick and choose what you want, and that's all too often what happens.

189
00:19:57,260 --> 00:20:07,260
 Science says the shroud is a 14th century fake, but so far no one has found a medieval technique to accurately reproduce the image.

190
00:20:08,260 --> 00:20:12,260
 No wonder the fascination with the Shroud of Turin continues.

191
00:20:12,260 --> 00:20:16,260
 The search for a method of creating the image on the shroud will go on.

192
00:20:16,260 --> 00:20:21,260
 But in the meantime, the failure is raising a new and controversial possibility.

193
00:20:21,260 --> 00:20:26,260
 Is it possible that the carbon-14 test itself was in some way flawed?

194
00:20:26,260 --> 00:20:33,260
 It's a possibility that's gaining currency because there is new evidence that places the Shroud of Turin earlier in time.

195
00:20:34,260 --> 00:20:39,260
 Historians have identified another Shroud of Christ in the 12th century in Constantinople.

196
00:20:39,260 --> 00:20:44,260
 And what I want to know is if this shroud could be the same as the one in Turin.

197
00:20:44,260 --> 00:20:56,260
 If it is, it would push the date of the Turin Shroud back by at least 160 years and challenge the accuracy of the carbon-14 test.

198
00:20:59,260 --> 00:21:05,260
 Evidence for a 12th century Shroud of Christ surfaced recently in a document called the Prey Manuscript.

199
00:21:05,260 --> 00:21:09,260
 It's in Hungary and takes its name from the scholar who first examined it.

200
00:21:09,260 --> 00:21:13,260
 It can be reliably dated to 1196.

201
00:21:13,260 --> 00:21:22,260
 This is one of its five illustrations and it shows Jesus being placed in his burial shroud.

202
00:21:24,260 --> 00:21:29,260
 Mertil Fleury-Lemberg is a textile expert who is charged with preserving the fabric of the Shroud.

203
00:21:29,260 --> 00:21:38,260
 She studied these images of Christ in the manuscripts and identified a number of features that reappear on the Turin Shroud.

204
00:21:38,260 --> 00:21:50,260
 The most obvious is that the figure on the Shroud has the arms crossed and the thumb hidden under the hand.

205
00:21:51,260 --> 00:22:03,260
 On the top you see the painting with the corpse laying on a white linen as one would expect, which is normal, a white linen.

206
00:22:03,260 --> 00:22:09,260
 And you see the arms crossed and you see the four fingers.

207
00:22:10,260 --> 00:22:18,260
 The thumb is invisible, is hidden, and that is also a connection. It's also visible the same on the Shroud.

208
00:22:18,260 --> 00:22:22,260
 Lemberg is also very aware of the geometric weave of the Shroud.

209
00:22:23,260 --> 00:22:34,260
 What is more important for a textile historian as I am, you see painted herringbone pattern.

210
00:22:34,260 --> 00:22:42,260
 And this herringbone pattern is a typical sign of the Shroud of Turin.

211
00:22:43,260 --> 00:22:47,260
 Another feature of the cloth are the holes bunched together in an L shape.

212
00:22:47,260 --> 00:22:59,260
